<p><b>  Armenia 
</b></p>
<p>9. The 19 February 2008 presidential elections were marked by various reports of 
violence at the polling stations.18 Following accusations by the runner-up, Levon Ter-
Petrossian, of widespread electoral fraud, demonstrations took place in Yerevan.19 
However, on 1 March 2008, the police reportedly used excessive force against protestors, 
and at least eight protestors were killed.20  
</p>
<p><b>  Bangladesh 
</b></p>
<p>10. General elections were held, for the first time in seven years, on 29 December 
2008.21 Eighteen people were reportedly injured in election day violence.22 On 30 
December 2008, two people died and more than a dozen were injured as a result of post-
election violence in a town outside of the country&#8217;s capital.23  
</p>
<p>11. Violent clashes between security forces and demonstrators opposing the ruling party 
have resulted in tens of deaths and hundreds wounded in the lead-up to the previous general 
election, between October 2006 and January 2007.24 The sustained violence and unrest 
eventually led to a cancellation of general elections to be held in January 2007 and caused 
the military to call for the implementation of emergency rule.25 Accordingly, at the time of 
the 2008 election, &#8220;Authorities ha[d] deployed 650,000 police officers and soldiers across 
the country to prevent violence and vote fraud.&#8221;26  
</p>
<p><b>  Cambodia 
</b></p>
<p>12. On 27 July 2008, Cambodia held national elections which returned the incumbent 
Cambodian People&#8217;s Party (CPP) to power. The European Union Election Observation 
Mission reported that, though election violence was markedly reduced in comparison to 
previous elections, instances of threats and intimidation remained, directed in particular 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p>Elections &#8211; Final Observation Report&#8221; (January 2009); Asia Network for Free Elections, &#8220;Report of 
the International Election Observation Mission&#8221; (December 2009). 
