<p><b>  Colombia 
</b></p>
<p>13. Electoral violence in the context of 2007 local elections was widespread, and the 
Public Advocate&#8217;s office estimated that over half of the country&#8217;s municipalities were at 
risk.31 At least 20&#8211;27 political candidates were killed, including mayoral and municipal 
council candidates.32 Overall, there were reports of at least 50 election-related deaths.33 
Observers tended to state that candidates were not targeted for their individual political 
affiliations, but that attacks represented opposition to the election process and the 
Government in general.34 While the FARC rebel group was responsible for many of the 
killings, criminal gangs and former paramilitaries are also reported to be responsible for 
some deaths.35  
</p>
<p>14. The Organization of American States election report notes that the killings and 
intimidation led to approximately 10 per cent of candidates giving up their nominations.36 
The report also notes that some voters reported being warned that they would be killed if 
they voted. In some areas, the FARC urged boycotts of the elections, in others, they 
threatened violence if citizens voted for certain parties.37  
</p>
<p><b>  Cote d&#8217;Ivoire 
</b></p>
<p>15. Presidential elections have been postponed numerous times since 2005 in C&#244;te 
d&#8217;Ivoire.38 On 19 February 2010, after President Gbagbo dissolved the electoral 
commission and the Government again postponed elections, protestors took to the streets 
